label: moi
name: moi
description: The mechanism of injury
source: 1. Participant 2. Participant relative/representative 3. Other person present who claim to know the participant 4. Hospital record
coding_instructions: Should be coded according to ICD-10, chapter XX, block V01-Y36, excluding codes listed in appendix 1 of the data dictionary. Use the online search engine http://apps.who.int/classifications/icd10/browse/2016/en#/XX. In participants for whom a traumatic mechanism is highly probable but you are unable to establish the exact mechanism at first contact, for example if the participant arrives unconscious with obvious external signs of trauma but no one is around to confirm the mechanism, enroll and attempt to confirm mechanism later.

name: dfct
description: The date when the participant had his or her first CT scan done after arriving at the hospital
source: 1. Direct observation by project officer 2. Hospital record 3. Participant 4. Participant relative 5. Other person present who claim to know the participant
coding_instructions: Code using the format YYYY-MM-DD, where YYYY is a four digit year, MM a two digit month and DD a two digit day. Assign the code 99 if the only ultrasound performed was performed before arrival to participating centre. If the participant had ultrasound-examinations both before arrival and after arrival to participating centre enter the date when the participant had his or her first ultrasound in the participating centre. If the participant did not have a ultrasound enter the code 0. If not available code as 999.

label: NumberOfSeriousInjuries
name: nosi
description: Number of serious injuries as estimated by the treating physician. A serious injury is here defined as an injury that warrants hospitalisation.
source: Treating physician
coding_instructions: The number of serious injuries is needed for calculation of the Kampala Trauma score. The number of serious injuries is estimated by the treating physician according to the categories below. Ask the treating physician and inform her or him about the definition of a serious injury as given above. The treating physician is the physician who would be triaging the patients, if there was a triage system in place. Hence, this person may vary across centres. In centres where the treatment is provided in the casualty by a CMO, then it is the CMO who should determine this variable. In centres where the CMO only decides which counter the patient should go to then it is the physician at that counter, for example surgery or orthopaedics, who assigns this variable. Code as 999 if unknown.
value_labels: "Nil/no serious injury","Single serious injury","Multiple serious injuries"
